\hypertarget{introduction}{%
\section{Introduction}\label{introduction}}

During this project, we will analyse two data sets in order to obtain
more insights about them and predict some objective variable. First, we
will approach the problem with a Linear Regression model, then, with the
second data set, we will try to model a Generalised Linear Model. These
are the data sets used:

\begin{itemize}
\item
  Airbnb:
  \url{https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/dipeshkhemani/airbnb-cleaned-europe-dataset}
\item
  Data scientist jobs:
  \url{https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/nikhilbhathi/data-scientist-salary-us-glassdoor}
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{linear-regression}{%
\section{Linear Regression}\label{linear-regression}}

\hypertarget{data-preparation}{%
\subsection{Data preparation}\label{data-preparation}}

For the first part of the assignment we will be using the Airbnb data
set. It consist of information about the Airbnb stays in some European
cities. The variables are the following:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  City: Amsterdam, Athens, Barcelona, Berlin, Budapest, Lisbon, Paris,
  Rome or Vienna
\item
  Price: continuous numeric variable
\item
  Day: WeekDay or Weekend
\item
  Room Type: Entire home/apt, Private room or Shared room
\item
  Shared Room: binary variable
\item
  Private Room: binary variable
\item
  Person capacity: integer from 2 to 6.
\item
  Superhost: binary variable
\item
  Multiple Rooms: binary variable
\item
  Business: binary variable
\item
  Cleanliness Rating: integer from 2 to 10.
\item
  Guest satisfaction: continuous numeric variable
\item
  Bedrooms: integer from 0 to 10
\item
  City center(km): continuous numeric variable
\item
  Metro distance(km): continuous numeric variable
\item
  Attraction index: continuous variable measuring the attraction to the
  Airbnb by the costumers
\item
  Normalised Atraction index: same but normalised
\item
  Restraunt Index: continuous variable measuring the restaurant
  performance index
\item
  Normalised Restraunt Index: same but normalised
\end{itemize}

The goal would be to predict the Price variable in terms of the others.
First, it is always a good idea to separate from the beginning the
training set (what the tool is going to see) from the testing set (used
only to validate predictions)

From the data obtained we can obtain the following insigths.

\hypertarget{price}{%
\subparagraph{Price}\label{price}}

The maximum of price seems to be too large for the mean and median. We
can get a better look with a boxplot:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{boxplot}\NormalTok{(AirbnbTrain}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Price)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\includegraphics{Project_Linear_-_GLM_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-6-1.pdf}

Although the maximum is an outlier, it is not alone, as we can observe
many other outliers that could be representing expensive Airbnb. In the
case the maximum would be alone, we could get rid of it, but in this
case this can be meaningful data.

Restraunt.Index}\label{attraction.index-and-restraunt.index}}

\hypertarget{explanatory-analysis}{%
\subsection{Explanatory analysis}\label{explanatory-analysis}}

In order to better comprehend our data, we need to plot it. Concretely,
we will have in mind plots respect to the objective variable, the price,
for trying to visualize a model for predicting it.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(AirbnbTrain, }\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(Price)) }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{geom\_density}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{fill=}\StringTok{"lightblue"}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{xlab}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Price"}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{ggtitle}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Price distribution"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\includegraphics{Project_Linear_-_GLM_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-11-1.pdf}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\DocumentationTok{\#\# from the statistics obtained before we know price has no 0 values as minimum is 34, so we can apply the logarithm to get a better distribution}

\FunctionTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(AirbnbTrain, }\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(Price))) }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{geom\_density}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{fill=}\StringTok{"lightblue"}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{xlab}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"log(Price)"}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{ggtitle}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Price distribution"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\includegraphics{Project_Linear_-_GLM_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-11-2.pdf}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{mean}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(AirbnbTrain}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Price))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## [1] 5.366296
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{exp}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{mean}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(AirbnbTrain}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Price)))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## [1] 214.0685
\end{verbatim}

As can be observed, Price is positive asymmetric, as most of the data is
located at the left of the distribution. In order to make the data more
symmetric, we need to take the logarithm. The log(Price) seems to follow
a Gaussian distribution with mean 5.36 (214.2107 ). This is beneficial
in terms of future prediction of the target, as it is symmetrical there
are no much extreme values and the regression would make better
predictions. However, still after the transformation the data are not
fully centered, but are slightly shifted to the left.

After observing the response variable individually, we can approximate
some regressions with plots. We now have in mind the Prices in terms of
the city, in order to better understand the data.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(AirbnbTrain, }\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(Price))) }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{geom\_density}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{group=}\NormalTok{City, }\AttributeTok{colour=}\NormalTok{City, }\AttributeTok{fill=}\NormalTok{City), }\AttributeTok{alpha=}\FloatTok{0.1}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{ggtitle}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Price distribution"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\includegraphics{Project_Linear_-_GLM_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-12-1.pdf}

Most of the cities have the same distribution, however we can observe
how Berlin has the highest prices while Amsterdam the lowest.

Some of the variables that we may think are important to determine the
price of an Airbnb are: distance to metro, distance to city center,
number of bedrooms, restaurant and attraction indexes. Let's observe
them.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(AirbnbTrain, }\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{x=}\NormalTok{City.Center..km., }\AttributeTok{y=}\FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(Price), }\AttributeTok{color=}\NormalTok{City)) }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{geom\_point}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{alpha=}\FloatTok{0.8}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{ggtitle}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Price vs City Center distance"}\NormalTok{) }
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\includegraphics{Project_Linear_-_GLM_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-13-1.pdf}

\hypertarget{simple-linear-regression-interpreting-the-betas}{%
\subsubsection{Simple linear regression: interpreting the
betas}\label{simple-linear-regression-interpreting-the-betas}}

Before developing a complex model for prediction, we will try to create
a simpler one where we avoid colinearities and better understand the
betas. Therefore, we first create a simple linear regresor with the
higher correlation variable: `Normalised Atraction Index'.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{simple\_linFit }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{lm}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(Price) }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\NormalTok{ Normalised.Attraction.Index, }\AttributeTok{data=}\NormalTok{AirbnbTrain)}
\FunctionTok{summary}\NormalTok{(simple\_linFit)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = log(Price) ~ Normalised.Attraction.Index, data = AirbnbTrain)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -2.5942 -0.3499 -0.0404  0.2918  4.6656 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)                 5.0064211  0.0048131 1040.16   <2e-16 ***
## Normalised.Attraction.Index 0.0306625  0.0003338   91.85   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.5107 on 33371 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2018, Adjusted R-squared:  0.2018 
## F-statistic:  8436 on 1 and 33371 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
\end{verbatim}

The simple linear regression model is defined as:
\(log(Price) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 N.Attraction.Index= 5.01 + 0.03 N.Attraction.Index\)

where \(\beta_1\) explains that a 1 unit increase in the normalized
attraction index would increase in 0.03 \% the log of the Price. We can
trust this model because the information gain is larger than the noise,
as the p\_value close to 0 confirms.

Furthermore, focusing on the global information, the residual standard
error, although is larger than the local, is still not that high. The
residual standard error is higher than the local because there is not
much information gain from the model, however, we can trust the model as
the information that \(\beta_1\) gives us has small standard error.

Finally, the \(R^2\) tell us about the information gain we get from the
model. Almost 20\%, while the remaining 80\% is noise. In general, this
is a difficult application, as the most correlated variable is only
giving us 20\% of the information, so it would be difficult to obtain
high \(R^2\) values on the test set. However, we always need to compare
with a benchmark for better conclusions (on the following sections).

To better comprehend how this model approaches the price prediction we
will plot the regression line:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\# Scatter plot}

\FunctionTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(AirbnbTrain, }\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ Normalised.Attraction.Index, }\AttributeTok{y =} \FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(Price))) }\SpecialCharTok{+}
  \FunctionTok{geom\_point}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{alpha =} \FloatTok{0.8}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{color=} \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}lightblue\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{+}
  \FunctionTok{geom\_smooth}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{method =} \StringTok{"lm"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{se =} \ConstantTok{FALSE}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{color =} \StringTok{"blue"}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{+}
  \FunctionTok{ggtitle}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Price vs Attraction Index regression"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
\end{verbatim}

\includegraphics{Project_Linear_-_GLM_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-22-1.pdf}

After understanding the model, let's evaluate how it predicts (this
result will be later compared with the benchmark and the complex linear
regression model).

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{pred\_simple}\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{exp}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{predict}\NormalTok{(simple\_linFit, }\AttributeTok{newdata=}\NormalTok{ AirbnbTest))}

\CommentTok{\#Let\textquotesingle{}s know validate the predictions, calculating R\^{}2 in the testing set}

\NormalTok{R2\_simple}\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{cor}\NormalTok{(pred\_simple, }\FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Price))}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2}
\NormalTok{R2\_simple}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## [1] 0.06822481
\end{verbatim}

As expected, \(R^2\) on the testing set is smaller than on the training
set (remember it was 0.2). Always is more difficult to predict future
values than present ones.

Finally, we can perform some diagnosis of our simple model to obtain
more conclusions:

\begin{itemize}
\item
  Residuals vs Fitted Values: this plot show as how our model is not
  homoscedastic, that is, the variance of the residuals is not constant
  with the Price, but it increases (negatively) for higher prices. This
  can be explained by the non symmetric distribution and the outliers.
\item
  Q-Q Residuals: the residuals are not normally distributed, as the
  outliers in the tails of the plot suggest issues with extreme
  residuals.
\item
  Scale-Location Plot: again this plots confirm us our model is not
  homocedastic, as there is a clear deviation on the line.
\end{itemize}

In general, we can say our model is not good for our objective.

\FunctionTok{par}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{mar =} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{))}

\FunctionTok{plot}\NormalTok{(simple\_linFit, }\AttributeTok{pch=}\DecValTok{23}\NormalTok{ ,}\AttributeTok{bg=}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}orange\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{,}\AttributeTok{cex=}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{predictive-analysis}{%
\subsection{Predictive analysis}\label{predictive-analysis}}

After understanding better how our data is constructed and being defined
a simple regression model, we will know try to develop the best model
for prediction. But first, we need to define the benchmark, from where
we have to improve.

\hypertarget{benchmark}{%
\subsubsection{Benchmark}\label{benchmark}}

In our case, as we are dealing with numerical continuous target, we
would consider the benchmark as predicting the mean (again using the
logarithmic transformation). This would be similar to the following
model: \(log(price)= \beta_0 \times 1\)

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{benchFit }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{lm}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(Price) }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{data=}\NormalTok{AirbnbTrain)}
\NormalTok{pred\_bench }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{exp}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{predict}\NormalTok{(benchFit, }\AttributeTok{newdata=}\NormalTok{AirbnbTest))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

As on the mean predictor the \(R^2\) can not be computed, we will use
the Root Mean Squared Error for comparison:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#MSE comparison: my model vs benchmark}
\NormalTok{RMSE\_simple}\OtherTok{=}\FunctionTok{sqrt}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{mean}\NormalTok{((pred\_simple }\SpecialCharTok{{-}} \FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Price))}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{))}
\NormalTok{RMSE\_bench}\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{sqrt}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{mean}\NormalTok{((pred\_bench }\SpecialCharTok{{-}} \FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Price))}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{))}
\NormalTok{RMSE\_simple}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## [1] 245.3246
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{RMSE\_bench}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## [1] 208.6998
\end{verbatim}

Clearly, our simple model is worse than the naive model, so we need to
improve it.

\hypertarget{complex-model-without-interactions}{%
\subsubsection{Complex model (without
interactions)}\label{complex-model-without-interactions}}

As a first approach to find our perfect model, we would fit a model with
all the variables we have. To do it, we first must change the format of
the variable `Superhost' on the test set for non finding programatic
errors when calculating the predictions.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Superhost}\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\FunctionTok{as.numeric}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{as.logical}\NormalTok{(AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Superhost))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{all\_linFit }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{lm}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(Price) }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\NormalTok{ ., }\AttributeTok{data=}\NormalTok{AirbnbTrain)}

\CommentTok{\# Predict on the test set}
\NormalTok{pred\_all }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{exp}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{predict}\NormalTok{(all\_linFit, }\AttributeTok{newdata =}\NormalTok{ AirbnbTest))}
  
  \CommentTok{\# Calculate MSE}
\NormalTok{RMSE\_all }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{sqrt}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{mean}\NormalTok{((pred\_all }\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{ AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Price)}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{))}
\NormalTok{R2\_all}\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{cor}\NormalTok{(pred\_all, AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Price)}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2}
\FunctionTok{summary}\NormalTok{(all\_linFit)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{R2\_all}

\begin{verbatim}

First, if we compare the \(R^2\) values in the training and in the
testing sets with the simple model, before we had 0.2 and 0.068,
respectively. The value for the training set has increased until 0.66 by
using all the variables, and the value on the testing set has increased
on until 0.3. Of course, this complex model is better than the simpler
one.

However, when comparing with the RMSE, we can see how the simple model
has the worst score with 245, followed by the complex with 239, and
again the benchmark is the best one with 208.

In order to try to improve this metrics, now we need to take into
account interactions between variables.

\hypertarget{complex-model-with-interactions}{%
\subsubsection{Complex model (with
interactions)}\label{complex-model-with-interactions}}

We first start by doing some feature selection, as does not have any
sense to add all the features because we will be adding more noise.
Therefore, we would try to find the best combination of the most
correlated variables: `Normalised.Attraction.Index',
`Normalised.Restraunt.Index', `Bedrooms' and `Person.Capacity'. In order
to do it, we will focus on both the \(R^2\) and the MSE, trying to find
the model that best maximizes the first one while minimasing the second
one.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{Y }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(AirbnbTrain}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Price)}

\NormalTok{variables\_to\_add}\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{list}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Normalised.Attraction.Index"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Normalised.Restraunt.Index"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Bedrooms"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Person.Capacity"}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{\#variables\_to\_add= list( "Bedrooms", "Person.Capacity", "Normalised.Attraction.Index", "Normalised.Restraunt.Index")}

\CommentTok{\#variables\_to\_add= list("Bedrooms", "Normalised.Attraction.Index", "Normalised.Restraunt.Index",  "Person.Capacity")}

\CommentTok{\#variables\_to\_add= list("Person.Capacity", "Normalised.Attraction.Index", "Normalised.Restraunt.Index", "Bedrooms" )}

\CommentTok{\# Create an empty data frame to store models,R2 and RMSE}
\NormalTok{rmse\_df }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{data.frame}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{RMSE =} \FunctionTok{numeric}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{length}\NormalTok{(variables\_to\_add)), }\AttributeTok{R2=} \FunctionTok{numeric}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{length}\NormalTok{(variables\_to\_add)), }\AttributeTok{Variables =} \FunctionTok{character}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{length}\NormalTok{(variables\_to\_add)), }\AttributeTok{stringsAsFactors =} \ConstantTok{FALSE}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{models }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{list}\NormalTok{()}

\CommentTok{\# Fit models and calculate MSE}
\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ (i }\ControlFlowTok{in} \FunctionTok{seq\_along}\NormalTok{(variables\_to\_add)) \{}
\NormalTok{  formula }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{as.formula}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{paste}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Y \textasciitilde{} "}\NormalTok{, }\FunctionTok{paste}\NormalTok{(variables\_to\_add[}\DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{i], }\AttributeTok{collapse =} \StringTok{" + "}\NormalTok{)))}
\NormalTok{  model }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{lm}\NormalTok{(formula, }\AttributeTok{data =}\NormalTok{ AirbnbTrain)}
  
  \CommentTok{\# Store the model}
\NormalTok{  models[[i]] }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ model}
  
  \CommentTok{\# Predict on the test set}
\NormalTok{  pred }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{exp}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{predict}\NormalTok{(model, }\AttributeTok{newdata =}\NormalTok{ AirbnbTest))}
  
  \CommentTok{\# Calculate MSE}
\NormalTok{  rmse }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{sqrt}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{mean}\NormalTok{((pred }\SpecialCharTok{{-}} \FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Price))}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{))}
  
\NormalTok{  R2}\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{cor}\NormalTok{(pred, }\FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Price))}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2}

  \CommentTok{\# Store MSE and variables in the data frame}
\NormalTok{  rmse\_df[i, }\StringTok{"RMSE"}\NormalTok{] }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ rmse}
\NormalTok{  rmse\_df[i, }\StringTok{"R2"}\NormalTok{] }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ R2}
\NormalTok{  rmse\_df[i, }\StringTok{"Variables"}\NormalTok{] }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{paste}\NormalTok{(variables\_to\_add[}\DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{i], }\AttributeTok{collapse =} \StringTok{", "}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{\}}

\CommentTok{\# Find the model with the lowest MSE}
\NormalTok{best\_model\_index }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{which.min}\NormalTok{(rmse\_df}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{RMSE)}
\NormalTok{best\_model }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ models[[best\_model\_index]]}

\CommentTok{\# Print results}
\FunctionTok{cat}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Best model includes variables:"}\NormalTok{, rmse\_df}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Variables[best\_model\_index], }\StringTok{"}\SpecialCharTok{\textbackslash{}n}\StringTok{"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\end{verbatim}

\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

## RMSE of the best model:
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{cat}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"R2 of the best model:"}\NormalTok{, rmse\_df}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{R2[best\_model\_index], }\StringTok{"}\SpecialCharTok{\textbackslash{}n}\StringTok{"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## R2 of the best model: 0.12769
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{rmse\_df}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
##       RMSE         R2
## 1 245.3246 0.06822481
## 2 232.1685 0.12768996
## 3 246.4637 0.16277580
## 4 247.6407 0.19576589
##                                                                            Variables
## 1                                                        Normalised.Attraction.Index
## 2                            Normalised.Attraction.Index, Normalised.Restraunt.Index
## 3                  Normalised.Attraction.Index, Normalised.Restraunt.Index, Bedrooms
## 4 Normalised.Attraction.Index, Normalised.Restraunt.Index, Bedrooms, Person.Capacity
\end{verbatim}

After trying several combinations, we lead to the conclusion that,
although adding the `Bedrooms' and `Person.Capacity' variables may
increase the \(R^2\), meaning is adding information, it also adds noise
as the RMSE increases a lot. By the RMSE the best model is the one with
only the first two variables (the ones more correlated), but we will
choose to add also Bedrooms so \(R^2\) is bigger enough.

Now, let's try to add interactions with the categorical variables. After
trying several combinations, we lead to the conclusion that `City' was
the most informative variable in order to interact with the indexes.
Later, we add `Bedrooms' and tried several more interactions, however,
any improvement was achieved. Finally, the best model we could fit was
the following.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{best\_linFit }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{lm}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(Price) }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\NormalTok{ City}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{(Normalised.Attraction.Index }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ Normalised.Restraunt.Index)}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2} \SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{sqrt}\NormalTok{(Bedrooms) , }\AttributeTok{data=}\NormalTok{AirbnbTrain)}

\CommentTok{\# Predict on the test set}
\NormalTok{pred\_best }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{exp}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{predict}\NormalTok{(best\_linFit, }\AttributeTok{newdata =}\NormalTok{ AirbnbTest))}
  
  \CommentTok{\# Calculate MSE}
\NormalTok{RMSE\_best }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{sqrt}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{mean}\NormalTok{((pred\_best }\SpecialCharTok{{-}} \FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Price))}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{))}
\NormalTok{R2\_best}\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{cor}\NormalTok{(pred, }\FunctionTok{log}\NormalTok{(AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Price))}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2}
\NormalTok{R2\_best}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## [1] 0.1957659
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{RMSE\_best}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## [1] 272.4953
\end{verbatim}

As we have said before, this is a difficult application, as many of the
variables do not add enough information. After trying many combinations,
we have lead to a model with \(R^2=0.2\) and \(RMSE = 272\). Having in
mind previous results, we have not been able to improve the benchmark,
but we have been able to reduce the noise from the model with all the
variables while maintaining the information gain.

For better conclusions we can perform some diagnosis. Contrary to the
simple model, this one has achieved to be more homocedastic, having
constant variance of the residuals and better distribution in general.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{plot}\NormalTok{(best\_linFit, }\AttributeTok{pch=}\DecValTok{23}\NormalTok{ ,}\AttributeTok{bg=}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}orange\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{,}\AttributeTok{cex=}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{prediction-intervals}{%
\subsubsection{Prediction Intervals}\label{prediction-intervals}}

Finally, we would evaluate the predictions of our model with the
prediction intervals.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{pred\_best }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{predict}\NormalTok{(best\_linFit, }\AttributeTok{newdata =}\NormalTok{ AirbnbTest, }\AttributeTok{interval=}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}prediction\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{y }\OtherTok{=}\NormalTok{ AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Price}
\NormalTok{yhat }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{exp}\NormalTok{(pred\_best)}

\CommentTok{\# Assuming pred.log contains the lower and upper prediction intervals}
\NormalTok{AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Pred }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{exp}\NormalTok{(pred\_best[, }\StringTok{"fit"}\NormalTok{])}
\NormalTok{AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Real }\OtherTok{=}\NormalTok{ y}
\NormalTok{AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Lower }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{exp}\NormalTok{(pred\_best[, }\StringTok{"lwr"}\NormalTok{])}
\NormalTok{AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Upper }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{exp}\NormalTok{(pred\_best[, }\StringTok{"upr"}\NormalTok{])}

\CommentTok{\# Create a data frame for plotting}
\NormalTok{plot\_data }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{data.frame}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{Real =}\NormalTok{ AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Real,}
                        \AttributeTok{Pred =}\NormalTok{ AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Pred,}
                        \AttributeTok{Lower =}\NormalTok{ AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Lower,}
                        \AttributeTok{Upper =}\NormalTok{ AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Upper)}
\CommentTok{\# Prediction Interval Plot}

\NormalTok{y\_limits }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{10005}\NormalTok{) }
\FunctionTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(plot\_data, }\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ Real, }\AttributeTok{y =}\NormalTok{ Pred)) }\SpecialCharTok{+}
  \FunctionTok{geom\_point}\NormalTok{() }\SpecialCharTok{+}
  \FunctionTok{geom\_ribbon}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{ymin =}\NormalTok{ Lower, }\AttributeTok{ymax =}\NormalTok{ Upper), }\AttributeTok{alpha =} \FloatTok{0.3}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{fill =} \StringTok{"blue"}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{+}
  \FunctionTok{labs}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{title =} \StringTok{"Scatter Plot of Real vs. Predicted"}\NormalTok{,}
       \AttributeTok{x =} \StringTok{"Real"}\NormalTok{,}
       \AttributeTok{y =} \StringTok{"Predicted"}\NormalTok{)}\SpecialCharTok{+}
  \FunctionTok{coord\_cartesian}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{ylim =}\NormalTok{ y\_limits)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\includegraphics{Project_Linear_-_GLM_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-32-1.pdf}

As we can observe, most of the points lies inside the shadow of the
prediction intervals. To better evaluate the exact quantity we can count
them.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\# Counting the points outside the intervals}
\NormalTok{outside\_interval\_count }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{sum}\NormalTok{(AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Real }\SpecialCharTok{\textless{}}\NormalTok{ AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Lower }\SpecialCharTok{|}\NormalTok{ AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Real }\SpecialCharTok{\textgreater{}}\NormalTok{ AirbnbTest}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Upper)}

\CommentTok{\# Calculating the coverage}
\NormalTok{total\_points }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{nrow}\NormalTok{(AirbnbTest)}
\NormalTok{coverage }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{round}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{100}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{(outside\_interval\_count }\SpecialCharTok{/}\NormalTok{ total\_points) }\SpecialCharTok{*} \DecValTok{100}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{digits=}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{\# Printing the coverage}
\FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{paste}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Percentage of points inside the intervals:"}\NormalTok{, coverage, }\StringTok{"\%"}\NormalTok{))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## [1] "Percentage of points inside the intervals: 95.5 %"
\end{verbatim}

Finally, our model is covering 95.5 \% of the points inside the
prediction intervals. That is, although before we determined that our
predictions were not that accurate due to bad results on RMSE, we can
say that our model is useful, as we are capturing well the noise. In
general, is more important to focus the performance of a model on the
intervals that on exact predictions, as usually we are interested on
knowing a close value of the price, but not interested on the exact one.

\hypertarget{data-preparation-1}{%

Continuing with the second dataset, we will focus on predicting the
average salary offered on several job postings related to the position
of Data Scientist. To do it, we will try to use a Generalised Linear
Model, but first, we need to clean our dataset.

The objective variable would be `Avg.Salary.K', that is an already
cleaned variable from `Salary.Estimate', measuring the mean of the
salaries offer in thousands of dollars. Therefore, we could get rid of
this last variable.

Apart from this one, we could observe several other variables that are
already clean on another column, as `Company.Name' and `company\_txt',
`Job.Title' and `job\_title\_sim', and finally, `Location' and
`Job.Location'.

Other variables we would eliminate are the `Job.Description', as is a
natural language column that would not gives as any valuable
information. Similarly, index is not giving any information so would be
also eliminated.

Finally, `Lower.Salary' and `Upper.Salary' would be erased as they can
easily predict the objective variable by performing the mean of the two,
so would be useless to develop a complete model if they alone can
predict it.

\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{numeric-variables}{%
\subsubsection{Numeric variables}\label{numeric-variables}}

This dataset has few numeric variables, naming, `Avg.Salary.K' (the
objective one), `Founded' (year of foundation of the company offering
the job), `Age' (of the company) and `Rating' (of the company). These
last two are redundant, as one can be obtained from the other one, so we
only would keep the age.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{Salary\_data\_Train }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{subset}\NormalTok{(Salary\_data\_Train, }\AttributeTok{select =} \SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{Founded)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

We first observe how many null values (-1) there are. As is not
significant, we keep all.

\hypertarget{explanatory-analysis-1}{%
\subsection{Explanatory Analysis}\label{explanatory-analysis-1}}

During this explanatory analysis, we would better focus on analyzing the
distribution of our objective variable and the possible relationships of
the other with it. As previously explained, our objective variable is
numeric representing the mean salary per year on thousands of dollars.
It is important to know the distribution before developing a GLM, so the
model can choose the appropriate link function. Therefore, we would try
to fit three different distributions and we would choose the best
approach.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{lambda }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{mean}\NormalTok{(Salary\_data\_Train}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Avg.Salary.K.)}
\NormalTok{mean\_val }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{mean}\NormalTok{(Salary\_data\_Train}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Avg.Salary.K.)}
\NormalTok{sd\_val }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{sd}\NormalTok{(Salary\_data\_Train}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Avg.Salary.K.)}

\NormalTok{rate  }\OtherTok{=}\NormalTok{ mean\_val}\SpecialCharTok{/}\FunctionTok{var}\NormalTok{(Salary\_data\_Train}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Avg.Salary.K.)}
\NormalTok{shape }\OtherTok{=}\NormalTok{ rate }\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{ mean\_val}

\NormalTok{xgrid }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{seq}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{250}\NormalTok{,}\FloatTok{0.1}\NormalTok{)}

\FunctionTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(Salary\_data\_Train, }\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(Avg.Salary.K.)) }\SpecialCharTok{+}
  \FunctionTok{geom\_density}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{fill =} \StringTok{"lightblue"}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{+}
  \FunctionTok{geom\_line}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{data =} \FunctionTok{data.frame}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{x =} \DecValTok{0}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{250}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{y =} \FunctionTok{dpois}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{0}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{250}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{lambda =}\NormalTok{ lambda)), }\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ x, }\AttributeTok{y =}\NormalTok{ y), }\AttributeTok{color =} \StringTok{"red"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{linewidth =} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{+} 
  \FunctionTok{geom\_line}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{data =} \FunctionTok{data.frame}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ xgrid, }\AttributeTok{y =} \FunctionTok{dnorm}\NormalTok{(xgrid, }\AttributeTok{mean =}\NormalTok{ mean\_val, }\AttributeTok{sd =}\NormalTok{ sd\_val)),}
            \FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ x, }\AttributeTok{y =}\NormalTok{ y), }\AttributeTok{color =} \StringTok{"blue"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{linewidth =} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{+}
  \FunctionTok{geom\_line}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{data =} \FunctionTok{data.frame}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ xgrid, }\AttributeTok{y =} \FunctionTok{dgamma}\NormalTok{(xgrid, }\AttributeTok{shape =}\NormalTok{ shape, }\AttributeTok{rate =}\NormalTok{ rate)),}
            \FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ x, }\AttributeTok{y =}\NormalTok{ y), }\AttributeTok{color =} \StringTok{"green"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{linewidth =} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{+}
  \FunctionTok{ggtitle}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Avg Salary distribution"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\includegraphics{Project_Linear_-_GLM_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-50-1.pdf}

As can be observed, the Gamma distribution is the one that better fits
our dataset, therefore, we would develop the GLM using it.

Furthermore, we can plot the objective variable in terms of other ones
to find relations. For example, here we observe how the salary
distribution differs a lot from one type of job offer from another.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(Salary\_data\_Train, }\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(Avg.Salary.K.)) }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{geom\_density}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{group=}\NormalTok{job\_title\_sim, }\AttributeTok{colour=}\NormalTok{job\_title\_sim, }\AttributeTok{fill=}\NormalTok{job\_title\_sim), }\AttributeTok{alpha=}\FloatTok{0.1}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{ggtitle}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Salary distribution by job title"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\includegraphics{Project_Linear_-_GLM_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-51-1.pdf}

If we perform the box plot of the previous relationship, we better
visualize how the offers for the `director' position are the ones with
biggest mean salary, or how the `data scientist' offers are the ones
with more variance of salaries.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(Salary\_data\_Train, }\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ job\_title\_sim, }\AttributeTok{y =}\NormalTok{ Avg.Salary.K.)) }\SpecialCharTok{+}
  \FunctionTok{geom\_boxplot}\NormalTok{() }\SpecialCharTok{+}
  \FunctionTok{labs}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{title =} \StringTok{"Boxplot between Avg Salary and Job Title"}\NormalTok{,}

  \FunctionTok{theme}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{axis.text.x =} \FunctionTok{element\_text}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{angle =} \DecValTok{45}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{hjust =} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\includegraphics{Project_Linear_-_GLM_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-52-1.pdf}

\hypertarget{model-development-and-interpretation}{%
\subsection{Model development and
interpretation}\label{model-development-and-interpretation}}

\hypertarget{benchmark-1}{%
\subsubsection{Benchmark}\label{benchmark-1}}

Following the same criteria as with the previous application, in order
to develop our model, we must first set the benchmark from where we
would try to improve the prediction RMSE, or at least, get as close as
possible.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{bench\_glm }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{glm}\NormalTok{(Avg.Salary.K. }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{ , }\AttributeTok{family =}\NormalTok{ Gamma, }\AttributeTok{data =}\NormalTok{ Salary\_data\_Train) }
\CommentTok{\#summary(bench\_glm)}

\NormalTok{pred\_bench\_glm}\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{predict}\NormalTok{(bench\_glm, }\AttributeTok{newdata=}\NormalTok{ Salary\_data\_Test)}

\CommentTok{\#Let\textquotesingle{}s know validate the predictions, calculating R\^{}2 in the testing set}

\CommentTok{\# Evaluate performance on the test set}
\NormalTok{RMSE\_test }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{sqrt}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{mean}\NormalTok{((pred\_bench\_glm }\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{ Salary\_data\_Test}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Avg.Salary.K.)}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{))}
\FunctionTok{cat}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"RMSE on test set:"}\NormalTok{, RMSE\_test, }\StringTok{"}\SpecialCharTok{\textbackslash{}n}\StringTok{"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## RMSE on test set: 110.9553
\end{verbatim}

\hypertarget{developing-the-model}{%
\subsubsection{Developing the model}\label{developing-the-model}}

We would make a first approach, in order to evaluate the marginal
effects of each variable into the model. Later, we would try to choose
the best variables to define the final model. As we can observed, with
this complex model we have reached \(R^2= 0.39\) and \(RMSE= 110.95\),
so, by using all the variables, we have many information but also more
noise, so RMSE is similar to benchmark.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\DocumentationTok{\#\# First glm}
\NormalTok{first\_glm }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{glm}\NormalTok{(Avg.Salary.K. }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\NormalTok{ job\_title\_sim}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ Rating }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ Hourly }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ Employer.provided }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ Python }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ spark }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ aws }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ excel }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ sql }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ sas }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ keras }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ pytorch }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ scikit }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ tensor }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ hadoop }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ tableau }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ bi }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ flink }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ mongo }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ google\_an }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ Size }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ Type.of.ownership }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ Sector }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ Revenue}\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ Job.Location }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ Age, }\AttributeTok{family =}\NormalTok{ Gamma, }\AttributeTok{data =}\NormalTok{ Salary\_data\_Train) }
\CommentTok{\#summary(first\_glm)}

\NormalTok{pred\_f\_glm}\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{predict}\NormalTok{(first\_glm, }\AttributeTok{newdata=}\NormalTok{ Salary\_data\_Test)}

\CommentTok{\#Let\textquotesingle{}s know validate the predictions, calculating R\^{}2 in the testing set}

\CommentTok{\# Evaluate performance on the test set}
\NormalTok{R2\_test }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{cor}\NormalTok{(pred\_f\_glm, Salary\_data\_Test}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Avg.Salary.K.)}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2}
\NormalTok{RMSE\_test }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{sqrt}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{mean}\NormalTok{((pred\_f\_glm }\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{ Salary\_data\_Test}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Avg.Salary.K.)}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{))}

\FunctionTok{cat}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"R{-}squared on test set:"}\NormalTok{, R2\_test, }\StringTok{"}\SpecialCharTok{\textbackslash{}n}\StringTok{"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

As we can observe, after analyzing the individual effects of the
variables on the model, we can get better inshigths. For example,
variables as `job\_title\_sim', `Hourly', `Python' or `Revenue' gives
many of the information to the model, as there is a clear difference
between the values and the objective function and the intervals are well
defined. However, other such as `sql' or `Job.Location' are not useful
for the model, because there is a lot of uncertainty on the intervals
and the mean salary value remains constant for all the x axis, so they
are only adding noise.

We develop another model with the most informative variables (still
without interactions). This model has lower \(R^2\) value, so we will
try on our final model add the necessary interactions to increase it by
using only the necessary variables.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\DocumentationTok{\#\# First glm}
\NormalTok{other\_glm }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{glm}\NormalTok{(Avg.Salary.K. }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\NormalTok{ job\_title\_sim }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ Hourly }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ Employer.provided   }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ google\_an }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ Size }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ Type.of.ownership }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ Sector }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ Python }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ Revenue }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ sas, }\AttributeTok{family =}\NormalTok{ Gamma, }\AttributeTok{data =}\NormalTok{ Salary\_data\_Train) }
\CommentTok{\#summary(first\_glm)}

\NormalTok{pred\_other\_glm}\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{predict}\NormalTok{(other\_glm, }\AttributeTok{newdata=}\NormalTok{ Salary\_data\_Test)}

\CommentTok{\#Let\textquotesingle{}s know validate the predictions, calculating R\^{}2 in the testing set}

\CommentTok{\# Evaluate performance on the test set}
\NormalTok{R2\_test }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{cor}\NormalTok{(pred\_other\_glm, Salary\_data\_Test}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Avg.Salary.K.)}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2}
\NormalTok{RMSE\_test }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{sqrt}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{mean}\NormalTok{((pred\_other\_glm }\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{ Salary\_data\_Test}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Avg.Salary.K.)}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{))}

\FunctionTok{cat}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"R{-}squared on test set:"}\NormalTok{, R2\_test, }\StringTok{"}\SpecialCharTok{\textbackslash{}n}\StringTok{"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{final-model}{%
\subsubsection{Final model}\label{final-model}}

After trying several combinations, we have reached to an \(R^2 = 0.31\),
close to the \(R^2 = 0.39\) of the more complex model, but only using

analyse the effects of them in the final model.

\begin{Shaded}

\DocumentationTok{\#\# First glm}
\NormalTok{final\_glm }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{glm}\NormalTok{(Avg.Salary.K. }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\NormalTok{ job\_title\_sim}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{Python  }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ Sector }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ Revenue}\SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{sas , }\AttributeTok{family =}\NormalTok{ Gamma, }\AttributeTok{data =}\NormalTok{ Salary\_data\_Train) }

\CommentTok{\# Evaluate performance on the test set}
\NormalTok{R2\_test }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{cor}\NormalTok{(pred\_final\_glm, Salary\_data\_Test}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Avg.Salary.K.)}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2}
\NormalTok{RMSE\_test }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{sqrt}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{mean}\NormalTok{((pred\_final\_glm }\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{ Salary\_data\_Test}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Avg.Salary.K.)}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{))}

\FunctionTok{cat}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"R{-}squared on test set:"}\NormalTok{, R2\_test, }\StringTok{"}\SpecialCharTok{\textbackslash{}n}\StringTok{"}\NormalTok{)}

\hypertarget{predictive-performance-prediction-intervals}{%
\paragraph{Predictive performance: Prediction
Intervals}\label{predictive-performance-prediction-intervals}}

We have already evaluate the \(R^2\) and \(RMSE\) values, let's know
plot the prediction intervals of the final model over the test set. We
would follow two different approaches:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Firstly, we would directly use the standard errors provided by the
  predict function for the gamma GLM model.
\item
  Secondly, we would calculate the prediction intervals by transforming
  the bounds on the linear scale using the inverse link function of the
  gamma distribution.
\end{itemize}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\DocumentationTok{\#\#First approach}
\NormalTok{pred\_final\_glm}\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{predict}\NormalTok{(final\_glm, }\AttributeTok{newdata=}\NormalTok{ Salary\_data\_Test, }\AttributeTok{type =} \StringTok{"response"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{se.fit =} \ConstantTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{\# Create a data frame for plotting}
\NormalTok{plot\_data }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{data.frame}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{Real =}\NormalTok{ Salary\_data\_Test}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Avg.Salary.K.,}
                        \AttributeTok{Pred =}\NormalTok{  pred\_final\_glm}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{fit,}
                        \AttributeTok{Lower =}\NormalTok{ pred\_final\_glm}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{fit }\SpecialCharTok{{-}} \FloatTok{1.96} \SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{ pred\_final\_glm}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{se.fit,}
                        \AttributeTok{Upper =}\NormalTok{ pred\_final\_glm}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{fit }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FloatTok{1.96} \SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{ pred\_final\_glm}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{se.fit)}
\CommentTok{\# Prediction Interval Plot}
\FunctionTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(plot\_data, }\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ Real, }\AttributeTok{y =}\NormalTok{ Pred)) }\SpecialCharTok{+}
  \FunctionTok{geom\_point}\NormalTok{() }\SpecialCharTok{+}
  \FunctionTok{geom\_ribbon}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{ymin =}\NormalTok{ Lower, }\AttributeTok{ymax =}\NormalTok{ Upper), }\AttributeTok{alpha =} \FloatTok{0.3}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{fill =} \StringTok{"blue"}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{+}
  \FunctionTok{labs}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{title =} \StringTok{"Scatter Plot of Real vs. Predicted"}\NormalTok{,}
       \AttributeTok{x =} \StringTok{"Real"}\NormalTok{,}
       \AttributeTok{y =} \StringTok{"Predicted"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\includegraphics{Project_Linear_-_GLM_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-61-1.pdf}

As we can observe, most of the points lies inside the shadow of the
prediction intervals. To better evaluate the exact quantity we can count
them.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\# Counting the points outside the intervals}
\NormalTok{outside\_interval\_count }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{sum}\NormalTok{(Salary\_data\_Test}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Avg.Salary.K. }\SpecialCharTok{\textless{}}\NormalTok{ pred\_final\_glm}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{fit }\SpecialCharTok{{-}} \FloatTok{1.96} \SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{ pred\_final\_glm}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{se.fit }\SpecialCharTok{|}\NormalTok{ Salary\_data\_Test}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Avg.Salary.K. }\SpecialCharTok{\textgreater{}}\NormalTok{ pred\_final\_glm}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{fit }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FloatTok{1.96} \SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{ pred\_final\_glm}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{se.fit)}

\CommentTok{\# Calculating the coverage}
\NormalTok{total\_points }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{nrow}\NormalTok{(Salary\_data\_Test)}
\NormalTok{coverage }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{round}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{100}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{(outside\_interval\_count }\SpecialCharTok{/}\NormalTok{ total\_points) }\SpecialCharTok{*} \DecValTok{100}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{digits=}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{\# Printing the coverage}
\FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{paste}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Percentage of points inside the intervals approach 1 :"}\NormalTok{, coverage, }\StringTok{"\%"}\NormalTok{))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## [1] "Percentage of points inside the intervals approach 1 : 43.1 %"
\end{verbatim}

Althougt on the plot we could visualize good predictions, when counting
the points inside the intervals we get less that half of them. Let's now
evaluate the second approach.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\DocumentationTok{\#\# Second approach}

\CommentTok{\# Extract necessary information}
\NormalTok{fit }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ pred\_final\_glm}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{fit}
\NormalTok{se\_fit }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ pred\_final\_glm}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{se.fit}

\CommentTok{\# Calculate prediction intervals using the inverse link function and Gamma distribution properties}
\NormalTok{lower\_limit }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ fit }\SpecialCharTok{*} \FunctionTok{exp}\NormalTok{(}\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\FloatTok{1.96} \SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{ se\_fit)}
\NormalTok{upper\_limit }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ fit }\SpecialCharTok{*} \FunctionTok{exp}\NormalTok{(}\FloatTok{1.96} \SpecialCharTok{*}\NormalTok{ se\_fit)}

\CommentTok{\# Create a data frame for plotting}
\NormalTok{plot\_data }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{data.frame}\NormalTok{(}
  \AttributeTok{Real =}\NormalTok{ Salary\_data\_Test}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Avg.Salary.K.,}
  \AttributeTok{Pred =}\NormalTok{ fit,}
  \AttributeTok{Lower =}\NormalTok{ lower\_limit,}
  \AttributeTok{Upper =}\NormalTok{ upper\_limit}
\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{y\_limits }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{10}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{18}\NormalTok{) }
\FunctionTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(plot\_data, }\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ Real, }\AttributeTok{y =}\NormalTok{ Pred)) }\SpecialCharTok{+}
  \FunctionTok{geom\_point}\NormalTok{() }\SpecialCharTok{+}
  \FunctionTok{geom\_ribbon}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{ymin =}\NormalTok{ Lower, }\AttributeTok{ymax =}\NormalTok{ Upper), }\AttributeTok{alpha =} \FloatTok{0.3}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{fill =} \StringTok{"blue"}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{+}
  \FunctionTok{labs}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{title =} \StringTok{"Scatter Plot of Real vs. Predicted"}\NormalTok{,}
       \AttributeTok{x =} \StringTok{"Real"}\NormalTok{,}
       \AttributeTok{y =} \StringTok{"Predicted"}\NormalTok{)}\SpecialCharTok{+}  \FunctionTok{coord\_cartesian}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{ylim =}\NormalTok{ y\_limits)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\includegraphics{Project_Linear_-_GLM_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-63-1.pdf}

With this approach is much more difficult to visualize in a plot the
prediction intervals, as the y axis limits are much larger, however,
when evaluating the points inside the intervals, we observe how the
predictions works perfectly.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\# Counting the points inside the intervals}
\NormalTok{inside\_interval\_count }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{sum}\NormalTok{(Salary\_data\_Test}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Avg.Salary.K. }\SpecialCharTok{\textgreater{}}\NormalTok{ lower\_limit }\SpecialCharTok{\&}\NormalTok{ Salary\_data\_Test}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{Avg.Salary.K. }\SpecialCharTok{\textless{}}\NormalTok{ upper\_limit)}

\CommentTok{\# Calculating the coverage}
\NormalTok{total\_points }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{nrow}\NormalTok{(Salary\_data\_Test)}
\NormalTok{coverage }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{round}\NormalTok{((inside\_interval\_count }\SpecialCharTok{/}\NormalTok{ total\_points) }\SpecialCharTok{*} \DecValTok{100}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{digits =} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{\# Printing the coverage}
\FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{paste}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Percentage of points inside the intervals approach 2:"}\NormalTok{, coverage, }\StringTok{"\%"}\NormalTok{))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## [1] "Percentage of points inside the intervals approach 2: 100 %"
\end{verbatim}

For the sake of interpretation, the first approach is better, however,
second approach gives us better prediction results. In general, we could
say that our final model has achieved to predict at least as well as the
benchmark, as the RMSE are equal, and has achieved to predict inside the
prediction intervals in most of the cases.

\hypertarget{conclusions}{%
\section{Conclusions}\label{conclusions}}

In conclusion, this notebook outlines two distinct approaches to
modeling a predictive application. In the context of the selected
datasets, linear regression presents challenges in enhancing the
benchmark, yet the final model successfully captures the majority of
data points within the prediction intervals.

Conversely, Generalized Linear Models prove to be more adept at fitting
the data distribution, yielding results comparable to the benchmark and
encompassing the majority of data points within the prediction
intervals.

In both scenarios, we emphasize the significance of interactions and
variable selection. These aspects play a crucial role in developing a
model that maximizes information while minimizing the impact of noise,
thereby contributing to a more robust and reliable predictive framework.
